I wanted a one-year break from Instagram and it ended up being 18 months. It has been filled with many shareable moments and milestones, but I wanted some present time with loved ones and a semi digital detox. Anybody else get that feeling?!

Not sure what is next for my digital journey but here is to embracing the extraordinary everyday moments. 

#family #love #beach #mother #parenting

I was off of here for a bit but popping back and let's see how it goes!

You will see my work as a social entrepreneur using fashion and media as my tools to drive change and champion gender equality.

What am I up to?

✊️ Founder and Executive Director of the @fashionimpactfund. We provide grants to female founders leading fashion workforce development solutions that accelerate women’s economic inclusion. 

🌱 Co-Founder of the United Nations Conscious Fashion and Lifestyle Network: An online platform bringing together industry stakeholders, media, governments, and UN system entities to collaborate and showcase responsible business practices.

🗞🎙Founding member @sdgmediazone and President of the Board @pvblicf: Focused on the upcoming United Nations General Assembly, collaborating with content creators and media partners to highlight actions and solutions in support of the SDGs.

Looking forward to what is ahead!

Photo credit: Maria Dominika

As we prepare for the SDG Media Zone to return to the United Nations General Assembly this September, I think back to our last major events in 2019 and juggling being a working mum on-site for 12+ hour days. I cherished the moments my son could be at work with me. 

We do not talk enough about the perpetual dance between guilt and pride whilst navigating motherhood and pursuing professional aspirations. I remind myself to celebrate my accomplishments and that being a loving parent and a career-driven woman is something to be proud of.

To all the working mothers and care-takers out there, here is an extra cheers for you today!

As a female founder, I've had my fair share of battles with imposter syndrome. In this pic, I am standing in front of 10 Downing Street about a year ago for a fashion industry convening.

What I realized inside the room was that I was not experiencing self-doubt about if I should be there as a small-town girl but instead the frustration of empty words from the leadership. There were female changemakers in the room that continue to challenge the status quo and disrupt industries transforming lives and communities. These are the collective I want shaping our nations.

I was grateful to be invited and it ignited me further to keep pushing for all voices and perspectives to be included.

Of course, I made sure that I had a Love Actually moment on the stairs (IYKYK 😉)

For nearly 11 years, our team at the PVBLIC Foundation have been powering new possibilities for social impact. 

As the President of the Board, I am so proud of the work that we do globally and our partnerships to mobilize media, data, and finance for sustainable impact.

Prime Minister of Sint Maarten, Silveria Jacobs, is breaking barriers and inspiring change by leading the way for female leadership.

First-time compiled data by UN Women this year shows that women represent 22.8 percent of Cabinet members heading Ministries and there are only 13 countries in which women hold 50 percent or more of the positions of Cabinet Ministers leading policy areas.

The significance of female leaders cannot be overstated. Studies consistently highlight the positive impact they have on policies, social cohesion, and economic development. Research reveals that companies with women in leadership positions demonstrate higher financial performance, innovation, and better decision-making, fostering an environment of diversity and inclusivity. Furthermore, when women occupy key roles in governance, there is a greater likelihood of addressing gender-specific issues and ensuring the representation and protection of women's rights.

In my era of embracing all as I am, a peaceful milestone of self-acceptance. Here is to loving our perfectly imperfect selves. 

Photo credit: Lisa Kato

In all of the impact work that I have ever done, advocating for women has been the toughest. In the pandemic I was so pissed off watching women be leaned on and failed, globally. I wanted to take whatever I had and put my energy into helping change things. It feels rebellious to speak up on women focused issues at a time when human rights are rolling backwards and constant hate arises.

The sad truth is that advocating for gender equality often invites resistance, backlash and even dismissal. The eye rolls or the awkward phone check to avoid hearing about gender pay gap, ill treatment of female garment workers, the lack of female leadership roles, the list goes on...

But I'm here for it...and the long-term.

When you are the one in the room banging on about how it is crucial to support female founders who are leading responsible business practices to empower women in the fashion workforce.

This is from the United Nations Commission on the Status of Women discussion exploring the role of fashion to advance equitable workforce development.

Yesterday I joined Australia, Fiji and India at the UN Headquarters in New York for a convening focused on SDG 6: Clean Water and Sanitation.

I addressed how the fashion industry's water-intensive production processes contribute to water scarcity and pollution. Additionally, how the industry's practices have a profound negative effect on women: environmentally, socially, and economically.

Strength and love in the palm of my hand.

This week my son had to join me for a work trip. Witnessing the curiosity in his eyes as he observed my work was so fun and beautiful.

Being a working mum can be challenging at times, juggling responsibilities and striving for success in both my career and motherhood. But in moments like these, when my worlds collide and I get to share my passion with my child, all the sacrifices feel worth it.

As I continue to navigate this balancing act, I'm grateful for every moment that allows me to intertwine my worlds and create memories like these.

As climate activation discussions ramp up in planning towards COP28, I reflect on when I digitally joined the Earth Day Network's Climate Education Hub at COP27. 

My message remains the same: the $2.5+ trillion-dollar fashion industry has to be held accountable for its role in negatively impacting climate change and women-led solutions that are trailblazing climate action should be fairly financed.

Honored to join Ambassador Giovanna Valverde Stark, Permanent Representative of Costa Rica to UNEP and UN Habitat, to discuss the imperative of sustainable lifestyles in combating overconsumption.

Grateful for the opportunity to engage with global female leaders, as we strive towards a fairer and greener future.

Recently at a non-fashion event I was speaking at, I was reminded how many people do not realize the power and damage of the fashion industry. A few reasons why I work for the fashion industry to be held accountable for its action and to be more responsible for sustainable change: 

➡️The fashion industry is one of the largest and most influential industries globally valued at approximately over $2.5T USD (McKinsey & Company)

➡️Fashion is one of the most labor-dependent industries in the world, 1 in 6 people in the world works in a fashion related job (United Nations Economic Commission for Europe)

➡️Approximately 80% of the 75 million garment workers in the fashion industry are women between the ages of 18 and 35, and the majority earn less than $3 per day (Fashion Revolution and Remake)

➡️25% of female garment workers in Bangladesh reported experiencing physical or verbal abuse at work (Worker Rights Consortium)

➡️Up to 100 billion garments are produced by the fashion industry every year. And each year, as much as 92 million tons of clothing ends up in landfills. Only 20% of textiles are collected for reuse or recycling globally

➡️Every year, approximately 500,000 tons of synthetic microfibers (equivalent to more than 50 billion plastic bottles) are released into the ocean through washing clothes (Ellen MacArthur Foundation)

Whilst the fashion industry currently relies on exploited labor and drives environmental degradation to deliver on trend driven prices and perpetual consumption rates, it has the potential to help create a more inclusive and sustainable economy. The sector needs to prioritize livable wages, fair labor practices, workers' rights, and sustainable production practices. The list goes on....

#fashion #impact #sustainability #sustainablefashion

📢 Great to share that our collaborative SDG Media Zone will be taking place at the upcoming United Nations General Assembly, September 2023.

Since 2016, the SDG Media Zone has been one of the main features of major events at the United Nations. It brings together world leaders, influencers, activists, experts, content creators, and media partners to highlight actions and solutions in support of the Sustainable Development Goals. 

Organized by the UN Department of Global Communications, in collaboration with the PVBLIC Foundation, the SDG Media Zone takes the conversation on advancing the 2030 Agenda out of the policy sphere and into the public discourse through impactful in-depth interviews and conversations on global issues that matter to people everywhere.

To date, we have hosted 28 SDG Media Zone’s in 9 countries featuring over 1.5k speakers and engaging over 1.1 billion people in 80 countries.

#Media #impact #sustainability

We created the United Nations Conscious Fashion and Lifestyle Network to be a dynamic online platform bringing together industry stakeholders, media, governments, and UN system entities to collaborate and showcase responsible business practices guided by the Sustainable Development Goals. 

To date, we have over 200 members in 64 countries who have pledged over 1200 commitments to the SDGs; with the priority goals for the industry showing as 12, 8, 13, 17, and 5. The Network's highest country engagement is currently in the USA, UK, India, France, Germany, Italy, Kenya and Brazil.

The United Nations Conscious Fashion and Lifestyle Network is a joint initiative of the Fashion Impact Fund and the United Nations Office for Partnerships.

Reports estimate that if women's economic participation were to match that of men's, it could add $28 trillion (or 26%) to the annual global GDP by 2025. The +$2.5T fashion industry plays a significant role in the global economy and contributes substantially to gender inequality. Women constitute a substantial portion of the fashion workforce, particularly in developing countries. However, they often face various barriers, including limited access to financing, training opportunities, and entrepreneurship support. To address these challenges and achieve women's economic inclusion, there is an urgent need to emphasize and invest in women's fashion workforce development programs.

At the Fashion Impact Fund, we provide grants to fashion skills and training programs for women to achieve decent employment and financial independence.

Our multifaceted mission aims to empower women, combat poverty and discrimination, and promote positive change within the fashion industry. By investing in women's education and employment, we can create lasting and transformative impact on their lives, communities, and the sector.

#fashion #finance #women

Kerry Bannigan, Executive Director, Fashion Impact Fund, shares: “I met Tamburai in 2019 in Europe where I learnt about the vision and mission of her work. Beyond a brand, ONEOFEACH developed The African Academy of Fashion as a fashion training facility to boost employment of local women while reinvigorating the traditional artisanal craft and manufacturing industry in Africa. The Fashion Impact Fund is pleased to have supported one of their fashion and creative business sector programs to strengthen the capacity of fashion job training and enhance women's economic inclusion.”

Check out the incredible work of mother and daughter duo Pauline and Tamburai Chirume who have trained over 100 women since 2019. The African Academy of Fashion focuses on practical and hands-on training using the African Fashion Curriculum, a first of its kind, to equip participants with the fundamental principles, techniques, knowledge, and a set of start-up tools that will enable them to utilize the rewarding skills of constructing garments and accessories from start to finish.

The Fashion Impact Fund’s next edition of the Conscious Fashion Campaign is live spotlighting female founders advancing equitable workforce development in the fashion industry in a digital billboard campaign during New York Fashion Week September 2023.

The honorees of the latest edition are Fashion Impact Fund 2023 grant recipients and are featured in the Conscious Fashion Campaign to further amplify the voices and achievements of their work. The honorees include:
💫 Ayesha Barenblat, Founder and CEO, Remake
💫 Jennifer Holloway, CEO, Fashion Enter Ltd
💫 Madhu Vaishnav, Founder and Director, Saheli Women 
💫 Devon Feldmeth; Okello Catherine “Ketty” Promise and Lauren Shipley, Co-Founders, Artisan Global 

The Conscious Fashion Campaign, an initiative of the Fashion Impact Fund in collaboration with the PVBLIC Foundation, seeks to shine a spotlight on the remarkable contributions of female founders who are leading the charge for a more inclusive and equitable fashion workforce. With an alarming statistic reported by Global Media Monitoring Project that women receive only 25% of news features globally, the campaign utilizes highly trafficked digital billboards in New York City that draws attention to women championing gender equality and decent work for all in the fashion sector.

Kerry Bannigan, Executive Director, Fashion Impact Fund moderated the Harnessing Culture and Community for Sustainable Development panel discussion at the SDG Media Zone during the 78th Session of the UN General Assembly featuring Sophia Kianni, Founder, Climate Cardinals and Samata Pattinson, Cultural Sustainability Pioneer, CEO, Black Pearl. 

In today's rapidly changing world, the importance of culture and community in driving sustainable development cannot be overstated. Culture is the backbone of any society, shaping values, traditions, and identities that influence how we interact with our environment whilst communities are the engines of change, and their active participation is essential for implementing solutions. By uniting cultures and communities in a shared vision for a more sustainable future, we can unlock the creative potential and collective wisdom needed to build resilient societies and protect the planet for generations to come. This panel explored how culture and community can be harnessed to promote social cohesion, environmental stewardship, and economic resilience.

The Fashion Impact Fund is continuing to support grant recipient Fashion-Enter LTD, a London based social enterprise which strives to be a center of excellence for learning and development of skills within the fashion and textiles industry. As part of the Fashion Impact Fund’s mission to support fashion workforce development solutions as a driver for women’s economic inclusion, we are pleased to finance 15 participants for a 12-week course for the Level 2 Certificate in Fashion and Textiles focused on developing the students' stitching and production skills.

Kerry Bannigan, Founder and Executive Director, Fashion Impact Fund adds: “We are pleased to provide a grant towards the program in support of Fashion-Enter’s commitment to fashion industry training, upskilling, and development for women to generate employment or enable entrepreneurship. We are grateful to Jenny and her team for leading workforce development courses that play a critical role in shaping a just transition for the future of fashion.”

Visit fashionimpactfund.org to learn more!

In the journey towards creating an impact, there are times when the path seems uncertain and your purpose appears elusive. The late nights, the sacrifices, and the setbacks—they all become part of the narrative. But just when it seems like the world is a chaotic jigsaw puzzle, a pivotal event can bring sudden clarity.

It's as if the universe conspires to remind you of the bigger picture and your fire within. Perhaps it's a conversation or a serendipitous encounter that amplifies your focus. In that moment, the pieces of the puzzle start falling into place, and you are reminded of the profound impact you can collectively drive.

Auliʻi Cravalho joined us as a narrator for the Environmental Symphony: The Movement, hosted by the Permanent Mission of the Kingdom of Tonga to the United Nations, to amplify the power of the human spirit to combat climate change, while highlighting the challenges faced by Small Island Developing States and frontline communities in every country across the globe.

Auliʻi first captured our hearts as the title role of Walt Disney Animation Studios' worldwide hit film MOANA.

Cravalho was born and raised in Hawaiʻi and focuses her time outside of film on Ocean Health & Livelihoods, partnering with SHEBA and MARS Coral Reef Restoration to announce the next extension in their HOPE GROWS project with Kuleana Coral Reefs; a nonprofit organization helping to restore and protect Hawaii's native ecosystem.

#climateaction #impact #climate

Kerry Bannigan, Founder and Executive Director, Fashion Impact Fund joined the Consulate General of Peru for NYC Jewelry Week to discuss the United Nations Fashion and Lifestyle Network.

As we find ourselves at the midway point of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), the jewelry industry is at a critical juncture to align with the global community and join the efforts towards achieving these Goals, for both people and the planet. From individual jewelers to global brands, the jewelry industry as a whole plays a pivotal role in this collective effort. The United Nations Fashion and Lifestyle Network offers a collaborative platform to jewelers and jewelry companies seeking to create a positive impact. In unity, fueled by creativity and the art of jewelry, we can foster partnerships that not only generate growth but also leave a lasting positive impact on our world.

Speakers also included Lucie Brigham, UN Office for Partnerships; Susan Wheeler, Responsible Jewelry Transformative and Andrea Jose Castro, Jewelry designer at Andrea Jose and Casa Collab with moderation by JB Jones, Co-Founder of NYC Jewelry Week.

RECIPROCITY and The Chicago Responsible Jewelry Conference presented the panel discussion in partnership with the United Nations Fashion and Lifestyle Network - a joint initiative of the UN Office for Partnerships and the Fashion Impact Fund.

#jewelry #NYC #SDGs #impact

In support of #16days of Activism against Gender-Based Violence and UNITE campaign that kicks off on 25 November, the PVBLIC Foundation and UN Women co-hosted the launch of the “UNSILENCED" docu-series that takes viewers on a journey across 16 different countries in six regions of the world to shed light on the continued magnitude and harmful impacts of violence against women and girls across the world.

This year’s theme is "Invest to prevent violence against women and girls” and calls on citizens to share the actions they are taking to create a world free from violence towards women. This year's campaign also calls on governments worldwide to share how they are investing in gender-based violence prevention. 

Join the global movement with the #NoExcuse campaign calling for urgent investments to prevent violence against women and girls.

UN Women, with the support of the PVBLIC Foundation and in partnership with 16 Days 16 Films, launched the “UNSILENCED” docu-series championing to end violence against women and girls. The series showcases human impact stories covering the transformation and progress made through the strength and determination of survivors, women’s rights activists, service providers, and more. It is also a call to action to inspire viewers to take a stand, get involved, advocate, and support the efforts of all women and girls to live a life free of violence.

Kerry Bannigan, Executive Director, Fashion Impact Fund and President, Board of Directors, PVBLIC Foundation delivered opening remarks as well as moderated a panel featuring Kalliope Mingeirou, UN Women Chief of End Violence Against Women and Filmmaker B. Monét.

UNSILENCED is a part of the 16 Days of Activism against Gender-Based Violence 2023 campaign. There is #NoExcuse - let’s end and prevent violence now.

We call for greater support to women’s rights movements so that they can continue to play their critical role in preventing and eliminating violence against women and girls. 

The urgent need to fund women's organizations fighting violence against women and girls cannot be overstated. Women’s rights organizations serve as the frontline champions in the drive for a more equitable and violence-free world.

In a world where the need for gender equality and violence prevention remains urgent, governments and institutions must acknowledge, empower, and invest in the unwavering efforts of women's organizations. Women’s rights organizations are committed to creating a safer, more equitable, and just society for women and girls everywhere, and a brighter and more promising future for all.

There is #NoExcuse for lack of support.

#16Days

At the Fashion Impact Fund, we focus on solutions that can help advance gender equality and decent work for all. We believe that education is the common thread to drive change globally. By providing grants to female founders, we not only aim to address the gender gap prevalent in entrepreneurship but also uplift diverse voices. By financing fashion workforce development, we aim to enable women to access training, education, and opportunities in the industry, leading to economic inclusion and a more equitable fashion sector overall. Our 2023 grantees that are providing valuable opportunities for women to lead and succeed include:

Ayesha Barenblat, Founder and CEO, Remake

Jennifer Holloway, CEO, Fashion Enter Ltd

Madhu Vaishnav, Founder and Director, Saheli Women

Devon Feldmeth; Okello Catherine “Ketty” Promise and Lauren Shipley, Co-Founders, Artisan Global

#FashionImpactFund #GenderEquality #Action #SDG5 #FemaleEmpowerment

Last month I met with the Prime Minister of Antigua and Barbuda, Gaston Browne, to support the signing of a Partnership Framework Agreement between PVBLIC Foundation and the government in a bid to prioritize small island nations and least developed countries in their journey to achieving sustainable development. By mobilizing technology and finance, we are committed to innovative solutions to mitigate the impacts of climate change on their communities. 

In May 2024, Antigua and Barbuda will host the 4th International Conference on Small Island Developing States (SIDS). The international community will gather to review SIDS’ sustainable development progress and propose a new decade of partnerships and solutions to supercharge their path to resilient prosperity.
